<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiangsu Forms Network To Help Farmers Compete </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0301025494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0220 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0301025494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nanjing, January 3 (XINHUA) -- East China's Jiangsu 
Province has formed a scientific service network to help farmers 
to compete on the market. 
  The province has registered 6,200 agro-technical societies 
with 240,000 members since farmers voluntarily set up the first 
one in 1980. 
  These societies are involved in more than 100 specialties 
covering plantation, breeding, gardening, sideline processing 
and rural enterprises. 
  Of the societies, about 1,000 focus on the study of 
technology, economic development and new products for rural 
industries. 
  Founded in 1985, the Nanfeng township-run Station Wagon Body 
Society in Zhangjiagang city, Jiangsu Province, has imported 12 
items of advanced technology and developed 18 new products. 
  As a result, it generated more than 80 million yuan in taxes 
and profits last year. 
  The province has formed a number of large special production 
bases and markets with the help of rural societies. 
  The Changzhang Vegetable Society in Tongshan county has set 
up a vegetable consultancy department, a seedling department and 
a production and marketing department to offer a package of 
related services. Its vegetables sell well across the country. 
  According to the provincial society of sciences and 
technology, Jiangsu will set up a provincial level federation of 
rural professional technology to better guide farmers to 
contribute in the market economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-44403 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi002_o_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shandong Plans Investment in Key Projects </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0201151994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1501 GMT 2 Jan 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW0201151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jinan, January 2 (XINHUA) -- East China's Shandong 
Province plans to earmark 10 billion yuan this year to fund some 
40 major projects in a bid to improve its infrastructure. 
  The projects will cover farming, water conservancy, energy, 
transport, communications and raw materials, according to 
provincial authorities. 
  To guarantee success, Shandong will introduce new measures 
including tendering, ways of investment and a responsibility 
system. 
  Last year, the province invested seven billion yuan in 36 
key 
projects, 16 of which have already been completed. 
  The newly-constructed Jinan-Qingdao highway, which links the 
province's inland capital to the scenic coastal city widely 
known for its beer, was the top project. The highway, of which 
the construction involved investments totalling 3.1 billion 
yuan, is expected to spark an economic take-off for the areas 
along the expressway. 
  Local experts estimate that the highway will bring about 
additional profits of more than five billion yuan every year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

