<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Sees `Record Amount' of Foreign Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401075094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0629 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, January 4 (XINHUA) -- China's largest 
metropolis reported a record amount of foreign investment used 
in 1993. 
  The municipal government approved 3,650 foreign-funded 
projects involving contractual investment totalling 7.016 
billion U.S. dollars last year, increases of 82 and 110 percent 
respectively over the previous year. 
  A municipal government official in charge of foreign 
investment said that of the 120 transnational corporations set 
up in the city, 60 percent began to make profits last year. 
  The city approved 205 large projects each with an investment 
exceeding 10 million U.S. dollars last year. These projects 
account for a total investment of 4.24 billion U.S. dollars, 60 
percent of the total. 
  The official noted that 1,037 of the approved projects are 
involved in banking, trading, commerce, real estate and 
improving urban infrastructural facilities. 
  By the end of last year, more than 3,000 industrial projects 
had gone into production, becoming a new force in Shanghai's 
economic development. 
  Experts here attributed the soaring investment in Shanghai 
to 
the large-scale development of the Pudong area, a 
newly-established economic zone, and the daily improvement of 
investment conditions. 
  So far, the city has approved 6,939 foreign-funded projects 
with contractual investment totalling 13.705 billion U.S. 
dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

