<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Feasibility' of Cross-Strait Marine Links Studied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401144794 Taipei CNA in English 1408 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lillian Lin] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 4 (CNA) -- The Board of Foreign Trade 
[BOFT] is studying the feasibility of direct marine links 
between Taiwan and Mainland China. 
  Despite the government ban on such links, many marine 
companies sail direct to the mainland coast. The Ministry of 
Economic Affairs will use the BOFT report in deciding whether to 
recommend that the ban on marine links be lifted. 
  BOFT Director-General Huang Yen-chao said that ships sailing 
to mainland ports are flying foreign flags which makes them 
difficult to police. He said direct marine links should be 
considered as long as they don't involve mutual recognition 
problems. 

</TEXT>

