<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deficit With Japan Expected To `Widen' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401103894 Taipei CNA in English 0900 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 4 (CNA) -- Taiwan's trade deficit 
with Japan is expected to further widen this year by 10 percent 
to U.S.$15.8 billion, Board of Foreign Trade (BOFT) officials 
predicted Tuesday [4 January]. 
  The deficit in 1993 grew by 12 percent to U.S.$14.4 billion, 
the officials said. 
  They estimated that Taiwan exports to Japan this year will 
grow 2 percent to U.S.$9.1 billion, but that imports from Japan 
will increase 7 percent to U.S.$25 billion. 
  The officials said export growth generating from the 
improved 
Japanese economy will be buffered by the depreciating value of 
the yen. 
  Last year's economic slowdown in Japan and high demand in 
Taiwan, in part due to the ongoing six-year national development 
plan, were reasons behind the snowballing trade deficit, the 
officials said. 
  Electronic and electric products accounted for 45 percent of 
imports from Japan, chemical products 10 percent, steel products 
8 percent, and auto parts 7 percent. 
  Agricultural products still made up the lion's share of 
Taiwan exports to Japan, but newly-emerged industrial products, 
including chemicals, computers, machinery, and steel, have 
replaced traditional industrial exports to Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

