<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Justice Minister: Prisons To Be `More Civilized' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401124594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1230 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 4 (XINHUA) -- Eighty percent of 
China's prisons and reform-through-labor centers will become 
modernized and more civilized by the year 2000, said Justice 
Minister Xiao Yang today. 
  He said prisons and rehabilitation centers are not only 
places where criminals are punished, but also places where they 
are reformed and re-educated. 
  "They offer a special kind of education," said the minister 
at a national conference of judicial officials, which opened 
today. 
  The minister said that criminals should be taught both to be 
law- abiding working people and people useful to the socialist 
market economy. 
  There were 300,000 inmates in China's prisons and 
reform-through- labor centers in 1993, he said. 
  Fewer than 0.12 percent of inmates escaped from prisons and 
fewer than 1 percent from reform centers in the first 11 months 
of last year, the minister said. 
  In recent years some major changes have occurred in the 
composition of prisoners, he said. Prisoners involved in 
criminal cases and economic cases are on the rise, and there are 
more offenders who are juveniles or former public employees, he 
said. 
  The minister asked that a network be set up within three to 
five years to help to offer jobs to people who have finished 
their sentences. 
  The prisons and reform-through-labor centers should be more 
open in terms of management, he said. The inmates should have 
more contacts with society, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

