<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Macao </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing, Lisbon Cooperate `Effectively' on Macao </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3112141193 Beijing XINHUA in English 1315 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW3112141193 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Macao, December 31 (XINHUA) -- A high-ranking 
Chinese official said here today that China and Portugal have 
cooperated effectively in implementing the Sino-Portuguese Joint 
Declaration and for the smooth transition in Macao. 
  Ambassador Guo Jiading, leader of the Chinese team of Sino- 
Portuguese Joint Liaison Group, made these remarks at a news 
conference here this afternoon. 
  Guo said that in 1993 Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Vice- 
President Rong Yiren and other senior officials had paid 
official visit to Portugal and Portuguese foreign minister and 
several other governmental officials had also visited China. 
  He said he was convinced that the high-level contacts 
between 
the two governments would further promote the consolidation and 
development of the Sino-Portuguese friendly relations of 
cooperation and enhance Macao residents' confidence on 
Sino-Portuguese cooperation in guaranteeing long-term stability 
in the territory. 
  Guo said that in 1993 both sides of the Sino-Portuguese 
Joint 
Liaison Group had initially consulted with each other and made 
marked achievements in handling affairs in the transitional 
period of Macao by observing the Joint Declaration and on the 
basis of mutual respect and mutual understanding. 
  In addition to the three major questions in the transitional 
period, namely the localization of public servants and law and 
officialization of Chinese language, and question about Macao's 
entry in international organizations, the two sides of the Joint 
Liaison Group also exchanged views on retirement pay for public 
servants, participation of Bank of China in note-issuing in 
Macao and others, Guo said. 
  He pointed out that the three questions are the major 
factors 
which have significant influence on the overall situation of the 
transitional period, saying that China has and will extend more 
efforts in pushing forward the settlement of the three major 
questions and others concerned. 

</TEXT>

