<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inner Mongolia Expands Access To `Outside World' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401102294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1002 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hohhot, January 4 (XINHUA) -- The landlocked Inner 
Mongolia Autonomous Region in north China further expanded its 
access to the outside world in 1993 and achieved greater 
progress in its border trade and tourism. 
  Eighteen open border posts have been set up along its 
4,200-km border line. Last year, some 470,000 Chinese and 
foreign business people went through these posts as well as 2.07 
million tons of cargo, up by a third than in 1992. 
  By now, the region has established an extensive transport 
network of railways, highways, water routes and airlines. 
  The Hulun Buir league in the north of the region, which is 
famous for its flourishing border trade, has set up seven 
trading posts along its 1,700-km-long border line with Mongolia 
and Russia. 
  To date, the league has established stable trade relations 
with more than 1,000 firms from 22 countries and regions, such 
as the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), Mongolia, the 
United States, Japan and the Republic of Korea. 
  Besides, the league has opened 12 tourist routes leading to 
the vicinity. In 1993, the volume of barter trade between 
Chinese, Russian and Mongolian tourists stood at 20 million yuan 
(3.4 million U.S. dollars) and one billion rubles (8 million 
U.S. dollars), respectively. 
  Manzhouli has always been called the "bridge of Eurasia" for 
its large trade handling volume. Since the city was approved by 
the government to be an open outlet in 1992, it has become 
China's largest border trade city, which has multiple functions, 
including exporting, processing, financial trade, international 
transport and storage. 
  Erenhot, another renowned border city, also launched 
large-scale construction projects last year. As more new roads, 
trade centers and storehouses are being built, the city is 
developing into a new grassland border trade center. 
  To make it possible to do business all the year round, a 
bridge is expected to be built across the Erhkuna river along 
the Sino- Russian border. 
  Meanwhile, air traffic is expanding. In addition to the 
weekly flight between Hohhot and Ulaanbaatar, capital of 
Mongolia, a through-flight between Hohhot and Hong Kong is to 
open to traffic before long. The region's second airport, 
Hailar airport, is to operate soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

