<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Approves Chang Jiang Regulation Reduction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3012054793 Beijing XINHUA in English 0205 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW3012054793 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, December 30 (XINHUA) -- It will be easier for 
foreign-registered vessels from January 1 onward to travel up 
the Chang Jiang River from Shanghai. 
  The director of the Wuhan-based Chang Jiang River Harbor and 
Shipping Superintendent's Bureau, Huang Jianping, said today 
that from January 1, all vessels sailing the international 
channel would need only to stop once at the Liuhe Anchorage on 
the upper stream in Shanghai Port to get in and out of the Chang 
Jiang River. 
  Currently vessels traveling along the Chang Jiang River have 
to anchor twice, when going in at Wusong Anchorage and going out 
at Liuhe, to allow Shanghai Port pilots and those of the Chang 
Jiang Shipping Bureau to go on board. 
  Too many stops and formalities, plus the problem of the 
shrinking Wusong Anchorage due to sludge deposits, have caused 
delays to many vessels and led to complaints by shipping 
companies, the director said. 
  After a working group investigated the problem, the Ministry 
of Communications recently approved the new scheme. 
  While improving the traffic and telecommunications at the 
Liuhe Anchorage, the director said that his bureau would also 
seek to expand the anchorage by 30 percent to allow 15 vessels 
of 30,000 dwt [deadweight tonnage] to anchor simultaneously. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

