<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Water Conservation, Irrigation Works Planned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3012164893 Beijing XINHUA in English 1427 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW3012164893 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, December 30 (XINHUA) -- China plans to 
increase irrigated farmland by 400,000 hectares next year and to 
control soil erosion in an area of two million hectares. 
  Niu Maosheng, minister of water resources, said here 
recently 
that reforms will be continued in the water resource 
organizations and the infrastructure construction of water 
resources will be strengthened, to support agricultural 
development. 
  Some flood control works will be built and some rivers will 
be dredged next year. Some 43 reservoirs in danger will be 
solidified and 38 will be checked and redesigned. 
  The minister said that efforts should also be made to solve 
the problem of drinking water shortages in urban and rural areas. 
  He also revealed that some hydropower stations with a total 
generating capacity of 1.1 million kw will be built next year. 
  To meet the target, Niu said, reforms should be carried out 
in the aspects of investment, real estate management, price 
administration, water resources laws and regulations, and 
service. 

</TEXT>

