<H3> <TI>   Premier Lien Chan on Southeast Asian Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Spokesman: Trip `Successful' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0401151194 Taipei CNA in English 1431 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li and Lian Chun-ti] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 4 (CNA) -- Presidential spokesman 
Raymond Tai said Tuesday [4 January] that Premier Lien Chan is 
engaging in successful "vacation diplomacy" in Malaysia and 
Singapore. 
  "It is encouraging, and will surely contribute to future 
cooperation with those countries," Tai said in a regular 
presidential press conference. 
  Lien began his two-leg private visit last Thursday. He has 
already met with the leaders and other ranking officials of the 
two Southeast Asian countries. 
  Tai said Lien's current trip is a realization of the 
"practical diplomacy" initiated by President Li Teng-hui. He 
said, however, that Li does not have plans to visit any foreign 
countries in the near future. 
  According to a CNA dispatch, meanwhile, Premier Lien and his 
wife spent a happy Tuesday in Singapore. 
  Lien started the day by playing golf with Singaporean Prime 
Minister Goh Chok Tong in the morning, and then took a ride on 
the Mass Rapid Transit [railway] system and toured the city in 
the afternoon. 
  Lien and his wife were honored by Senior Minister Li Kuan 
Yew 
at a dinner party held at the presidential office Tuesday night. 
Several Singaporean cabinet ministers were also in attendance. 
  Lien will leave Singapore Wednesday, winding up his first 
overseas trip since he assumed the premiership early last year. 

</TEXT>

