<H3> <TI>   Dalai Lama Visit Said `Likely' in March </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401150894 Taipei CNA in English 1411 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 4 (CNA) -- Tibet's spiritual leader, 
the Dalai Lama, is likely to visit Taiwan in March, an official 
with the Mongolian &amp; Tibetan Affairs Commission said Tuesday 
[4 
January]. 
  The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed a desire to visit 
Taiwan, and earlier reports said he would visit this month. 
  The official said the commission welcomes the Dalai Lama to 
preach on the island, noting that the number of Buddhists in the 
Dalai Lama's sect has been on the rise here. 
  The Dalai Lama has on several occasions given credit to 
Taiwan for its political democratization, prosperity, and 
freedom of press and religion, the official indicated. "He 
should come here to learn for himself the situation about 
Taiwan." 
  The Dalai Lama has been in exile in India since he fled 
Tibet 
in 1959 after mainland Chinese troops crushed an uprising there. 

</TEXT>

