<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report on CIA Destroying Radiation Records </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0501043694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0302 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0501043694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed "report": "CIA Destroyed Files on Human </F>
Radiation Testing"] 
  [Text] Washington, January 4 (XINHUA) -- The U.S. Central 
Intelligence Agency (CIA) had destroyed documents on radioactive 
tests it conducted on human beings during the Cold War, news 
reports said today. 
  Steven Aftergood of the Federation of American Scientists 
said the full extent of the testing may never be known to the 
public. 
  Aftergood told the REUTERS News Service that the CIA 
conducted covert radiation tests from 1953 to 1967 but many 
files on the tests were destroyed in 1973. 
  The revelation came one day after the establishment of a 
joint task force that would coordinate the investigation efforts 
by about half a dozen of government departments on the tests. 
  The inter-agency probe would involve the Energy Department, 
the Defense Department, the Veterans Affairs Department and the 
National Aeronautics and Space Administration. 
  The White House said it expects that the CIA would cooperate 
with the government-wide investigation of the tests, probably 
involved some 800 U.S. citizens, some without knowing the nature 
of the testings. 
  Media reports said the testing subjects included retarded 
children fed radioactive milk and cereal and inmates received x- 
rays. 
  Aftergood said CIA had also done drug testing and "the drug 
testing was part of a larger program which included studies on 
the effects of radiation and a number of other things." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-44524 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi003_h_94001" </HT>


