<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Says Social Stability `Threatened' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0501024894 Hong Kong THE STANDARD in English 4 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK0501024894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong THE STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Cary Huang, China editor] </F>
  [Text] China's social stability is being threatened by an 
influx of migrants, potential spiralling price rises and other 
social problems following the rush for sweeping reforms this 
year, an official Chinese government report says. 
  The widening income gap between the rich and the poor, 
increasing economic crimes, official corruption, labour disputes 
and receding national unity among ethnic minorities are also 
listed as major threats in the report. 
  Ordered by the State Council, China's cabinet, the report 
tries to identify potential social problems that might crop up 
this year when the country is set to fully embrace a 
quasi-capitalistic market economy. The move underlined the 
Chinese leadership's serious concerns over possible social 
unrest and their caution over the on- going reforms. 
  Senior leaders, including Communist Party chief Jiang Zemin 
and Premier Li Peng recently talked of "keeping a balance among 
economic growth, reforms and social stability". 
  Chinese sources yesterday said the internal report, compiled 
by a team made up of experts from the State Council's Research 
Office, the Economic Forecasting Centre, and economists and 
sociologists from research institutes, also suggested the 
government should take the "necessary measures" to minimise the 
"unsettling factors" from further development. The report 
predicts that with a comparatively tight money supply and a 
reduction in capital investment this year, the major coastal 
cities' labour markets will not be able to accommodate the 
increasing pressure of migrant job-seekers. It also says the 
reforms are likely to force more urban employees out of work. 
  Inflation is expected to continue to rise, while prices of 
staple foods, major consumer products and construction materials 
will pick up, following the government's move to free more 
prices from central control. The report adds that reforms 
should be introduced only as long as consumers can bear the 
inevitable inflation. 
  In an interview with the official Xinhua News Agency 
published on Sunday, Li said too rapid strides in price reform 
would cause instability. 
  The government reimposed controls on the price of grain and 
other staple foods in many large cities in late December, after 
watching prices soar 30 to 40 percent in a month. Government 
officials said the sudden rise was partly due to panic buying in 
anticipation of even higher prices in 1994 and partly because of 
farmers hoarding their grain for the same purpose. 
  The report also warns that the income gap between the 
richest 
and the poorest in China has widened to an alarming scale. It 
said the income gap in China was at a ratio of between 1:15 to 
1:20, while in developed nations it was about 1:10. The gap is 
likely to become wider following the massive privatisation of 
state assets. The gap between the rich coastal regions and the 
impoverished western hinterland will increase, although the 
latter is developing and the living standards of the people 
there are rising, the report says. 
  However, the report says China can overcome these problems 
if 
the government takes the "appropriate measures" and is cautious 
in implementing its reforms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

