<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Emergency' Meeting on Grain Transfer Work Held </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0501090094 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 0650 
GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0501090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 5 Jan (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE)--To relax 
grain supply tensions in some provinces and municipalities, 
China's Ministry of Internal Trade and State Grain Reserve 
Bureau held an emergency grain transfer work meeting in Beijing 
some days ago. At the meeting, the principle of doing unified 
planning with due consideration for all concerned and ensuring 
major areas was reaffirmed and concrete arrangements were made 
for grain allocations and transfers between provinces in the 
first quarter of the year. 
  According to the plan worked out at the meeting, in current 
grain allocations and transfers, it is necessary to implement 
the principle of making unified planning with due consideration 
for all concerned and ensuring major areas. The major areas to 
which grain will be transferred include eight provinces which 
are short of grain and three municipalities. The provinces are 
Guizhou, Yunnan, Guangxi, Guangdong, Fujian, Hainan, Zhejiang, 
and the eastern part of Sichuan, and the municipalities are 
Beijing, Tianjin, and Shanghai. When making arrangements for 
the grain transfer, priority will be given to special grain 
reserves, grain for market regulation, and grain for the 
fulfillment of trade contracts. 
  It has been learned that for January this year, various 
provinces have worked out special transportation plans, adding 
140 special trains for this purpose. This has added burdens to 
communications and transportation. The departments concerned 
are now discussing the issue with the railroad department to 
solve this problem. It is expected that in January, a plan to 
transport some 700,000 metric tons of grain will be fulfilled, 
including those which have already been transported, which will 
be 100,000 metric tons more than the original plan. In February 
and March, it is planned that a total of 4.1 million metric tons 
of grain will be transported. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

