<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation Uses Coking Gas in Making Sponge Iron </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401103594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0952 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shengyang, January 4 (XINHUA) -- China has become 
the first country in the world to use coking gas as power in 
making sponge iron, a major material for high-grade alloy steel. 
  The scientific breakthrough, scored by the Benxi Iron and 
Steel Company in northeast China's Liaoning Province, is claimed 
to have reduced the contents of phosphorus, sulphur and carbon, 
all detrimental to the quality of steel, to far below the 
international standards. 
  Sponge iron is an important material for various high-grade 
alloy steel used in military, aerospace, petrochemical and other 
key industries. 
  Currently sponge iron production worldwide is powered by 
either natural gas or coal, a method characterized by 
complicated techniques and high costs. 
  According to specialists at the benxi iron and steel 
company, 
the new method is simpler and costs less. 
  The specialists also discovered that the iron ore in a local 
open mine has a very low content of phosphorus, sulphur and 
other harmful elements, and therefore is the best raw material 
for the production of good quality sponge iron. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

