<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Senate Delegation Arrives in Beijing 4 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0401134094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1327 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0401134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 4 (XINHUA) -- A U.S. Senate 
delegation led by its Energy and Natural Resources Committee 
Chairman Bennett Johnston arrived in Beijing this morning to 
start a five-day tour of China. 
  Liu Shuqing, president of the Chinese Institute of Foreign 
Affairs (CIFA), held a working meeting with the delegation this 
afternoon, during which the two sides exchanged views on the 
improvement and development of Sino-U.S. bilateral relations. 
  The current visit is designed to explore the prospects of 
expanding trade and co-operation in the field of energy, and 
exchanging views on a variety of issues such as trade in 
military products, nuclear proliferation and issues related to 
China's most- favored-nation status. 
  As CIFA's guest, the delegation is a continuation of a 
series 
of visits by groups of U.S. Senators who have toured China since 
last August, and is the first delegation to visit China since 
the Sino- U.S. summit in Seattle between Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin and U.S. President Bill Clinton, a CIFA official said. 
  Among the delegation are seven Senators, including the 
Senate's minority leader, Alan Simpson. 
  The delegation is the biggest yet to visit China from the 
U.S. Senate, the official said, and senior Chinese leaders will 
meet it before it leaves for Guangzhou, the capital of south 
China's Guangdong Province. 

</TEXT>

