<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Leading Official' on Stabilizing Commodity Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0501124694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1235 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0501124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 5 (XINHUA) -- China will continue 
to take effective measures to stabilize commodity prices, 
especially the prices of grain and edible oil, a leading 
official from the State Planning Committee said here today. 
  The rise of grain and edible oil prices since November last 
year has been brought under control, he said, and the prices of 
these commodities in the markets throughout China are stable as 
a series of measures have been taken by governments at all 
levels. 
  At present, most of the state-owned grain shops sell grain 
at 
marked prices with unlimited supply, the official said, adding 
that in some areas the prices of grain and edible oil have 
dropped. 
  China will continue to strengthen the management of the 
markets and control and supervision of the prices, he said. 
  "Those who seek exorbitant profits through driving up prices 
will be punished severely," he said. 
  He mentioned that a series of reform plans involving taxes, 
finance and investment will come out this year. "The government 
will take effective measures to soften the negative impacts of 
these plans on society," he stressed. 
  In addition, measures such as increasing salaries, and 
subsidies and incomes of farmers will be taken. 
  Meanwhile, China will spare no efforts to develop its 
economy 
to guarantee supply, the official said. 
  The state reserves of grain in 1994 will be sufficient, 
while 
the supply of edible oil, sugar and some articles of everyday 
use will meet the demand. 
  "China has the conditions to keep prices low and markets 
stable," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

